ection have been too hasty. Instead, he demonstrates how capitalism and liberalism have fashioned and ultimately imperilled agriculture in the area. This fascinating case study reveals the contradictions and deficiencies of contemporary farmland preservation paradigms, highlighting the challenges of forging more socially just and ecologically rational food systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgriculturexHistoryzOntariozHolland Marsh. 0aAgriculturezOntariozHolland MarshxHistory. 0aLand use, RuralxHistoryzOntariozHolland Marsh. 0aLand use, RuralzOntariozHolland MarshxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy (see also SOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food) .2bisacsh1 aMarsh, Culture’s, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486547040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865470/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles